$BODY = <<<'HTML'
<p>"What if it gets worse until I can hear nothing at all?" It is one of the first fears when the ringing does not go away. The answer, for almost everyone, is reassuring: tinnitus is not the road to deafness. Here is what science really says.</p>

<h2>Tinnitus is a symptom, not a "destroyer" of hearing</h2>
<p>The ringing does not harm the ear. It is often the signal that some fine sensory cells are already a little worn — from age or past loud noises — and the brain reacts by creating a sound in their place. But this process does not progress on its own toward deafness: the hearing of people with tinnitus generally remains stable for years.</p>

<h2>How common it is (and why you are not alone)</h2>
<p>Tinnitus affects approximately <span class="num">14.4%</span> of adults — nearly <span class="num">740</span> million people worldwide (Jarach, JAMA Neurology 2022). Most live with the ringing without any deterioration of hearing. Only a minority experiences severe distress, and even in those cases the problem is the discomfort related to the sound, not hearing loss.</p>

<h2>What really protects hearing</h2>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Protect your ears from loud noise.</strong> Concerts, tools, headphones at high volume: here yes, care is needed, because intense noise can damage hearing (and sometimes trigger tinnitus).</li>
  <li><strong>Moderate headphone volume.</strong> A practical rule: no more than <span class="num">60%</span> for no more than <span class="num">60</span> minutes continuously.</li>
  <li><strong>Have your hearing checked if in doubt.</strong> A basic audiogram gives a reference point and dispels uncertainty.</li>
</ul>

<h2>The signs that deserve examination</h2>
<p>Most tinnitus is harmless, but some presentations should be evaluated promptly by an ENT: ringing in one ear only, pulsatile tinnitus (in the rhythm of the heartbeat), sudden onset or a noticeable hearing loss. These are not signs of impending deafness, but something to be investigated.</p>

<h2>In short</h2>
<p>Tinnitus does not lead to deafness. It is a brain signal, not a disease that progresses. Protect your ears from loud noise, do a check-up if you want certainty and manage the condition with sound and calm: the fear of deafness, almost always, is just fear.</p>
